<br>
&quot;Good God or Good Universe?&quot;<br>
<br>
Is there a God? What can astronomy say about this question? Is teleology making a comeback in the recent discoveries of numerous cosmological constants that seem to imply that &quot;In some sense the universe must have known we were coming&quot; (Heeren, 1995)? Or, are these constants merely the multiple, and almost mathematically inconceivable, chance coincidences of a universe that finally got it right after billions of big bangs and big crunches? As I often tell patients whom I'm hypnotizing, &quot;I don't know and you don't know, but your (perhaps) unconscious knows.&quot; <br>
<br>
Honestly, of course, no one can answer this question with apodictic certainty. We would have to have infinite knowledge, and even then subjectivity would be involved.<br>
In fact, how can you have any knowledge without subjectivity? This tenet is the cornerstone of postmodernism and a second cousin of quantum mechanics, third cousin of relativity. To make a long story short, people decide the answer to the God question on the basis of some gut-level, experiential &quot;information&quot; which is an amalgam of psychological need, cultural/familial influences (including so-called objective &quot;facts&quot;), and ONLY GOD KNOWS WHAT ELSE. None of the foregoing three are mutually exclusive--indeed they all may work together, even blending into each other, to bring an individual to some point of awareness that he or she has crossed the bridge from the intellectually &quot;safe&quot; land of agnosticism, and decided, on faith, that the answer is either &quot;Yes&quot; or &quot;No.&quot;<br>
<br>
The movie, &quot;Contact,&quot; addressed these questions brilliantly and movingly. (Sagan's novel, from which the final screenplay departed by several leaps and bounds, basically made a strong pitch for atheism.) In the movie, Ellie Arroway, a SETI astronomer played by Jody Foster, asks Palmer Judd, a renegade liberal ex-priest-turned-protestor against the technoculture played by Matthew McConahey, &quot;How do you know your experience of God was not just a projection of some personal need of yours?&quot; He replies, &quot;I'm a pretty intelligent guy, Ellie....No, this was too big for even my mind to comprehend.&quot; Later, she says, &quot;Where is your proof for God?&quot; He replies, &quot;Proof....Proof....Let me ask you a question, Ellie: Did you love your father?&quot;<br>
She answers, &quot;Yes, very much!&quot; He then says, &quot;Prove it!&quot;<br>
<br>
At the end of the movie, Ellie, back from her adventure through an electromagnetically created wormhole to the Vega star-system, has no proof whatsoever that the journey, which she recorded as taking 18 hours and which those on earth saw as lasting only seconds, had really taken place. She is left to say that she can't prove it, but knows it happened because her experience was convincingly real to her. In case you haven't been keeping score, subjectivity wins (with a small token to objectivity, which I won't reveal in case you haven't seen the movie) and people, including moi, are crying at the end of this terrific experience of a movie.<br>
<br>
Long ago, the Psalmist, based on his experiences, addressed a God he subjectively believed to be there and said: &quot;When I consider your heavens, the work of your fingers, the moon and the stars which you have set in place, what is man that you are mindful of him, the son of man that you care for him?&quot; (Psalm 8:3/4). I can't prove there's a God. I only know the question is important. But, based on my experience, long ago I decided to live &quot;as if&quot; the answer to the question is &quot;Yes.&quot;<br>
I can honestly say that, even if the answer is &quot;No,&quot; I have been a better, kinder and more loving person than I would have been had I not decided so.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulomasi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lomasi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/11/02 7:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=147>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Simple, Clear and Poweful</span><hr size=1> Lurkeen there are Budist chaplins... and chaplins of every religion.  Just had to point that out.  <br>
